\cl CHAP.
\c 1
\iex 1 Elkanah a Leuite hauing two wiues, worshippeth yeerely at Shiloh. 4 Hee cherisheth Hannah, though barren, and prouoked by Peninnah. 9 Hannah in griefe, prayeth for a childe. 12 Eli first rebuking her, afterwards blesseth her. 19 Hannah hauing borne Samuel, stayeth at home till he be weaned. 24 She presenteth him, according to her vow, to the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 1 ¶ Now there was a certaine man of Ramathaim Zophim, of mount Ephraim, & his name \add was\add* Elkanah, the sonne of Ieroham, the sonne of Elihu, the sonne of Tohu, the sonne of Zuph, an Ephrathite;
\v 2 And he had two wiues, the name of the one \add was\add* Hannah, and the name of the other Peninnah: and Peninnah had children, but Hannah had no children.
\v 3 And this man went vp out of his citie \x + \xo 1:3 \xt Deut. 16.16.\x*\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Hebr. from yeere to yeere.\f*yeerely, to worship and to sacrifice vnto the \nd LORD\nd* of hostes in Shiloh; and the two sonnes of Eli, Hophni, and Phinehas, the Priests of the \nd LORD\nd*, \add were\add* there.
\v 4 ¶ And when the time was, that Elkanah offered, he gaue to Peninnah his wife, and to all her sonnes, and her daughters, portions.
\v 5 But vnto Hannah he gaue \f + \fr 1:5 \ft Or, a double portion.\f*a worthy portion: (for he loued Hannah, but the \nd LORD\nd* had shut vp her wombe.
\v 6 And her aduersary also \f + \fr 1:6 \ft Hebr. angred her.\f*prouoked her sore, for to make her fret, because the \nd LORD\nd* had shut vp her wombe.)
\v 7 And \add as\add* he did so yeere by yeere, \f + \fr 1:7 \ft Or, from the time that she &c. Hebr. from her going vp.\f*when she went vp to the house of the \nd LORD\nd*, so she prouoked her; therefore she wept, and did not eat.
\v 8 Then said Elkanah her husband to her, Hannah, why weepest thou? and why eatest thou not? and why is thy heart grieued? Am not I better to thee, then ten sonnes?
\v 9 ¶ So Hannah rose vp after they had eaten in Shiloh, and after they had drunke; (now Eli the Priest sate vpon a seat by a poste of the Temple of the \nd LORD\nd*.)
\v 10 And shee \add was\add* \f + \fr 1:10 \ft Hebr. bitter of soule.\f*in bitternesse of soule, and prayed vnto the \nd LORD\nd*, and wept sore.
\v 11 And she vowed a vow, and said, O \nd LORD\nd* of hostes, if thou wilt indeed looke on the affliction of thine handmayd, and remember me, and not forget thine handmayd, but wilt giue vnto thine handmayd \f + \fr 1:11 \ft Hebr. seed of men.\f*a man childe, then I will giue him vnto the \nd LORD\nd* all the dayes of his life, and \x + \xo 1:11 \xt Num. 6.5. iudg. 13.5.\x*there shall no rasor come vpon his head.
\v 12 And it came to passe as she \f + \fr 1:12 \ft Hebr. multiplied to pray.\f*continued praying before the \nd LORD\nd*, that Eli marked her mouth.
\v 13 Now Hannah, shee spake in her heart; onely her lippes mooued, but her voice was not heard: therefore Eli thought she had beene drunken.
\v 14 And Eli said vnto her, How long wilt thou be drunken? put away thy wine from thee.
\v 15 And Hannah answered, and said, No, my lord, I \add am\add* a woman \f + \fr 1:15 \ft Hebr. hard of spirit.\f*of a sorrowfull spirit: I haue drunke neither wine nor strong drinke, but haue powred out my soule before the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 16 Count not thine handmaid for a daughter of Belial: for out of the abundance of my \f + \fr 1:16 \ft Or, meditation.\f*complaint and griefe, haue I spoken hitherto.
\v 17 Then Eli answered, and said, Goe in peace: and the God of Israel grant \add thee\add* thy petition, that thou hast asked of him.
\v 18 And she said, Let thine handmaid finde grace in thy sight. So the woman went her way, and did eate, and her countenance was no more \add sad\add*.
\v 19 ¶ And they rose vp in the morning early, and worshipped before the \nd LORD\nd*, and returned, and came to their house to Ramah: and Elkanah knewe Hannah his wife, and the \nd LORD\nd* remembred her.
\v 20 Wherefore it came to passe when the \f + \fr 1:20 \ft Hebr. reuelation of dayes.\f*time was come about, after Hannah had conceiued, that shee bare a sonne, and called his name \f + \fr 1:20 \ft That is, asked of God.\f*Samuel, \add saying\add*; Because I haue asked him of the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 21 And the man Elkanah, and all his house, went vp to offer vnto the \nd LORD\nd* the yeerely sacrifice, and his vowe.
\v 22 But Hannah went not vp; for shee said vnto her husband, I will not goe vp vntill the childe be weaned, and \add then\add* I will bring him, that he may appeare before the \nd LORD\nd*, and there abide for euer.
\v 23 And Elkanah her husband said vnto her, Do what seemeth thee good, tary vntill thou haue weaned him, only the \nd LORD\nd* establish his word: so the woman abode, and gaue her sonne sucke vntill she weaned him.
\v 24 ¶ And when shee had weaned him, shee tooke him vp with her, with three bullocks, and one Ephah of floure, and a bottle of wine, and brought him vnto the house of the \nd LORD\nd* in Shiloh: and the childe \add was\add* young.
\v 25 And they slew a bullocke, and brought the childe to Eli.
\v 26 And she said, Oh my lord, \add as\add* thy soule liueth, my lord, I \add am\add* the woman, that stood by thee heere, praying vnto the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 27 For this childe I prayed, and the \nd LORD\nd* hath giuen me my petition, which I asked of him:
\v 28 Therefore also I haue \f + \fr 1:28 \ft Or, returned him, whom I have obtained by petition to the LORD.\f*lent him to the \nd LORD\nd* as long as hee liueth, \f + \fr 1:28 \ft Or, hee whom I haue obteined by petition, shalbe returned.\f*he shall be lent to the \nd LORD\nd*. And he worshipped the \nd LORD\nd* there.
\c 2
\iex 1 Hannahs song in thankefulnesse. 12 The sinne of Elies sonnes. 18 Samuels ministerie. 20 By Elies blessing, Hannah is more fruitfull. 22 Eli reprooueth his sonnes. 28 A prophecie against Elies house.
\v 1 ¶ And Hannah prayed, and said, My heart reioyceth in the \nd LORD\nd*, mine horne is exalted in the \nd LORD\nd*: my mouth is inlarged ouer mine enemies: because I reioyce in thy saluation.
\v 2 \add There is\add* none holy as the \nd LORD\nd*: for \add there is\add* none beside thee: neither \add is there\add* any Rocke like our God.
\v 3 Talke no more so exceeding proudly, let \add not\add* \f + \fr 2:3 \ft Hebr. hard.\f*arrogancie come out of your mouth: for the \nd LORD\nd* \add is\add* a God of knowledge, and by him actions are weighed.
\v 4 The vowes of the mightie men \add are\add* broken, and they that stumbled are girt with strength.
\v 5 \add They that were\add* full, haue hired out themselues for bread: and \add they that were\add* hungry, ceased: so that the barren hath borne seuen, and she that hath many children, is waxed feeble.
\v 6 \x + \xo 2:6 \xt Deut. 32.39. wisd. 16.13. tob. 13.2.\x*The \nd LORD\nd* killeth and maketh aliue, he bringeth downe to the graue, and bringeth vp.
\v 7 The \nd LORD\nd* maketh poore, and maketh rich: he bringeth low, and lifteth vp.
\v 8 \x + \xo 2:8 \xt Psal. 113.7.\x*He raiseth vp the poore out of the dust, \add and\add* lifteth vp the begger from the dunghill, to set \add them\add* among princes, and to make them inherit the throne of glory: for the pillars of the earth \add are\add* the \nd LORD\nd*s, and hee hath set the world vpon them.
\v 9 He will keepe the feet of his saints, and the wicked shall bee silent in darkenesse; for by strength shall no man preuaile.
\v 10 The aduersaries of the \nd LORD\nd* shalbe broken to pieces: \x + \xo 2:10 \xt Chap.7.10.\x*out of heauen shal he thunder vpon them: the \nd LORD\nd* shall iudge the ends of the earth, and he shal giue strength vnto his king, and exalt the horne of his Anointed.
\v 11 And Elkanah went to Ramah to his house, and the child did minister vnto the \nd LORD\nd* before Eli the Priest.
\v 12 ¶ Now the sonnes of Eli \add were\add* sonnes of Belial, they knewe not the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 13 And the priests custome with the people \add was, that\add* when any man offred sacrifice, the priestes seruant came, while the flesh was in seething, with a fleshhooke of three teeth in his hand,
\v 14 And he strooke \add it\add* into the panne, or kettle, or caldron, or pot: all that the flesh-hooke brought vp, the priest tooke for himselfe: so they did in Shiloh vnto all the Israelites that came thither.
\v 15 Also before they burnt the fat, the priests seruant came, & said to the man that sacrificed, Giue flesh to roste for the priest, for he wil not haue sodden flesh of thee, but raw.
\v 16 And \add if\add* any man said vnto him, Let them not faile to burne the fat \f + \fr 2:16 \ft Hebr. as on the day.\f*presently, and \add then\add* take \add as much\add* as thy soule desireth: then hee would answere him, \add Nay\add*, but thou shalt giue \add it\add* mee now: and if not, I will take it by force.
\v 17 Wherefore the sinne of the yong men was very great before the \nd LORD\nd*: for men abhorred the offering of the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 18 ¶ But Samuel ministred before the \nd LORD\nd*, \add being\add* a child, \x + \xo 2:18 \xt Exod. 28.4.\x*girded with a linnen Ephod.
\v 19 Moreouer, his mother made him a litle coate, and brought \add it\add* to him from yeere to yeere, when she came vp with her husband, to offer the yeerely sacrifice.
\v 20 ¶ And Eli blessed Elkanah, and his wife, and said, The \nd LORD\nd* giue thee seed of this woman, for the \f + \fr 2:20 \ft Or, petition which hee asked, &c.\f*loane which is lent to the \nd LORD\nd*. And they went vnto their owne home.
\v 21 And the \nd LORD\nd* visited Hannah, so that shee conceiued, and bare three sonnes, and two daughters: and the child Samuel grew before the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 22 ¶ Now Eli was very olde, and heard all that his sonnes did vnto all Israel, and how they lay with the women that \f + \fr 2:22 \ft Hebr. assembled by troupes.\f*assembled \add at\add* the doore of the Tabernacle of the Congregation
\v 23 And he said vnto them, Why doe ye such things? for \f + \fr 2:23 \ft Or, I hear euill words of you.\f*I heare of your euil dealings, by all this people.
\v 24 Nay my sonnes: for \add it is\add* no good report that I heare; yee make the \nd LORD\nd*s people to \f + \fr 2:24 \ft Or, to cry out.\f*transgresse.
\v 25 If one man sinne against another, the Iudge shall iudge him: but if a man sinne against the \nd LORD\nd*, who shall intreat for him? Notwithstanding they hearkened not vnto the voice of their father, because the \nd LORD\nd* would slay them.
\v 26 (And the child Samuel grew on, and was in fauour, both with the \nd LORD\nd*, and also with men.)
\v 27 ¶ And there came a man of God vnto Eli, and saide vnto him, Thus saith the \nd LORD\nd*, Did I plainely appeare vnto the house of thy father, when they were in Egypt in Pharaohs house?
\v 28 And did I chuse him out of all the tribes of Israel, \add to be\add* my Priest, to offer vpon mine altar, to burne incense, to weare an Ephod before me? and \x + \xo 2:28 \xt Leuit. 10.14.\x*did I giue vnto the house of thy father, all the offerings made by fire of the children of Israel?
\v 29 Wherefore kicke ye at my sacrifice, and at mine offering, which I haue commaunded \add in my\add* habitation, and honourest thy sonnes aboue mee, to make your selues fat with the chiefest of all the offrings of Israel my people?
\v 30 Wherefore the \nd LORD\nd* God of Israel saith, I sayd indeede \add that\add* thy house, & the house of thy father should walke before me for euer: but now the \nd LORD\nd* saith, Be it farre from mee; for them that honour me, I will honour, and they that despise me, shall be lightly esteemed.
\v 31 Behold, the dayes come, that I will cut off thine arme, and the arme of thy fathers house, that there shall not be an old man in thine house.
\v 32 And thou shalt see \f + \fr 2:32 \ft Or, the affliction of the Tabernacle, for all the wealth which God would haue giuen Israel.\f*an enemie \add in my\add* habitation, in all \add the wealth\add* which \add God\add* shall giue Israel, and there shall not bee an olde man in thine house for euer.
\v 33 And the man of thine, \add whom\add* I shall not cut off from mine Altar, \add shall be\add* to consume thine eyes, and to grieue thine heart: and all the increase of thine house shall die \f + \fr 2:33 \ft Heb. men.\f*in the floure of their age.
\v 34 And this shall bee a signe vnto thee, that shall come vpon thy two sonnes, on Hophni and Phinehas: in one day they shall die both of them.
\v 35 And I will raise me vp a faithfull Priest, \add that\add* shall doe according to \add that\add* which \add is\add* in my heart and in my mind, and I will build him a sure house, and hee shall walke before mine Anointed for euer.
\v 36 And it shall come to passe, \add that\add* euery one that is left in thine house, shal come \add and\add* crouch to him for a piece of siluer, and a morsel of bread, and shall say, \f + \fr 2:36 \ft Heb. ioyne.\f*Put me (I pray thee) into \f + \fr 2:36 \ft Or, Somewhat about the Priesthood.\f*one of the Priests offices, that I may eat a piece of bread.
\c 3
\iex 1 How the word of the \nd LORD\nd* was first reuealed to Samuel. 11 God telleth Samuel the destruction of Elies house. 15 Samuel, though loth, telleth Eli the vision. 19 Samuel groweth in credit.
\v 1 ¶ And the child Samuel ministred vnto the \nd LORD\nd* before Eli: and the word of the \nd LORD\nd* was precious in those daies; \add there was\add* no open vision.
\v 2 And it came to passe at that time, when Eli \add was\add* layd downe in his place, and his eyes beganne to waxe dimme, \add that\add* he could not see;
\v 3 And yer the lampe of God went out in the Temple of the \nd LORD\nd*, where the Arke of God \add was\add*, and Samuel was layd downe to sleepe;
\v 4 That the \nd LORD\nd* called Samuel, and he answered, Here \add am\add* I.
\v 5 And he ranne vnto Eli, and sayd, Here \add am\add* I, for thou calledst me. And he said, I called not; lie downe againe. And he went and lay downe.
\v 6 And the \nd LORD\nd* called yet againe, Samuel. And Samuel arose, and went to Eli, and said, Here \add am\add* I, for thou diddest call me. And he answered, I called not, my sonne; lie downe againe.
\v 7 \f + \fr 3:7 \ft Or, thus did Samuel, before he knew the LORD; and before the word of the LORD was reuealed vnto him.\f*Now Samuel did not yet know the \nd LORD\nd*, neither was the word of the \nd LORD\nd* yet reuealed vnto him.
\v 8 And the \nd LORD\nd* called Samuel againe the third time. And hee arose, and went to Eli, and said, Here \add am\add* I, for thou diddest call me. And Eli perceiued that the \nd LORD\nd* had called the childe.
\v 9 Therefore Eli said vnto Samuel, Go, lie downe, & it shal be, if he call thee, that thou shalt say, Speake \nd LORD\nd*, for thy seruant heareth. So Samuel went, and lay downe in his place.
\v 10 And the \nd LORD\nd* came, and stood and called as at other times, Samuel, Samuel. Then Samuel answered, Speake, for thy seruant heareth.
\v 11 ¶ And the \nd LORD\nd* sayd to Samuel, Behold, I will doe a thing in Israel, at which, both the eares of \x + \xo 3:11 \xt 2.Kin. 21.12.\x*euery one that heareth it, shall tingle.
\v 12 In that day, I will performe against Eli, all \add things\add* which I haue spoken concerning his house: \f + \fr 3:12 \ft Hebr. beginning and ending.\f*when I begin, I will also make an end.
\v 13 \f + \fr 3:13 \ft Or, and I will tell him, &c.\f*\x + \xo 3:13 \xt Chap. 2.29,30,31, &c.\x*For I haue tolde him, that I will iudge his house for euer, for the iniquitie which hee knoweth: because his sonnes made themselues \f + \fr 3:13 \ft Or, accursed.\f*vile, and he \f + \fr 3:13 \ft Heb. frowned not vpon them.\f*restrained them not.
\v 14 And therefore I haue sworne vnto the house of Eli, that the iniquitie of Elies house shall not be purged with sacrifice, nor offering for euer.
\v 15 ¶ And Samuel lay vntill the morning, and opened the doores of the house of the \nd LORD\nd*: and Samuel feared to shew Eli the vision.
\v 16 Then Eli called Samuel, and said, Samuel my sonne. And he answered, Here \add am\add* I.
\v 17 And he said, What is the thing that the \nd LORD\nd* hath said vnto thee? I pray thee hide it not from mee: God doe so to thee, and \f + \fr 3:17 \ft Hebr. so adde.\f*more also, if thou hide any \f + \fr 3:17 \ft Or, word.\f*thing from me, of all the things that hee said vnto thee.
\v 18 And Samuel tolde him \f + \fr 3:18 \ft Heb all the things, or words.\f*euery whit, and hid nothing from him. And he said, It \add is\add* the \nd LORD\nd*: Let him doe what seemeth him good.
\v 19 ¶ And Samuel grew, and the \nd LORD\nd* was with him, and did let none of his words fall to the ground.
\v 20 And all Israel from Dan euen to Beer-sheba, knew that Samuel was \f + \fr 3:20 \ft Or, faithfull.\f*established to bee a Prophet of the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 21 And the \nd LORD\nd* appeared againe in Shiloh: for the \nd LORD\nd* reueiled himselfe to Samuel in Shiloh, by the word of the \nd LORD\nd*.
\c 4
\iex 1 The Israelites are ouercome by the Philistines at Aben-Ezer. 3 They fetch the Arke, vnto the terrour of the Philistines. 10 They are smitten againe, the Arke taken, Hophni and Phinehas are slaine. 12 Eli at the newes, falling backward, breaketh his necke. 19 Phinehas wife, discouraged in her trauaile with Ichabod, dieth.
\v 1 ¶ And the word of Samuel \f + \fr 4:1 \ft Or, came to passe: Hebr. was.\f*came to all Israel. Now Israel went out against the Philistines to battell, and pitched beside Eben-ezer: and the Philistines pitched in Aphek.
\v 2 And the Philistines put themselues in aray against Israel: and when \f + \fr 4:2 \ft Hebr. the battell was spread.\f*they ioyned battell, Israel was smitten before the Philistines: and they slew of \f + \fr 4:2 \ft Hebr. the aray.\f*the armie in the field, about foure thousand men.
\v 3 ¶ And when the people were come into the campe, the Elders of Israel said, Wherefore hath the \nd LORD\nd* smitten vs to day before the Philistines? Let vs \f + \fr 4:3 \ft Hebr. take vnto vs.\f*fetch the Arke of the Couenant of the \nd LORD\nd* out of Shiloh vnto vs, that when it commeth among vs, it may saue vs out of the hand of our enemies.
\v 4 So the people sent to Shiloh, that they might bring from thence the Arke of the Couenant of the \nd LORD\nd* of hostes, which dwelleth betweene the Cherubims: and the two sonnes of Eli, Hophni, and Phinehas \add were\add* there, with the Arke of the Couenant of God.
\v 5 And when the Arke of the Couenant of the \nd LORD\nd* came into the campe, all Israel shouted with a great shout, so that the earth rang againe.
\v 6 And when the Philistines heard the noise of the shout, they said, What \add meaneth\add* the noise of this great shout in the campe of the Hebrewes? And they vnderstood, that the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd* was come into the campe.
\v 7 And the Philistines were afraid, for they saide, God is come into the campe. And they said, Woe vnto vs: for there hath not bene such a thing \f + \fr 4:7 \ft Hebr. yesterday, or the third day.\f*heretofore.
\v 8 Woe vnto vs: who shall deliuer vs out of the hand of these mightie Gods? these \add are\add* the Gods that smote the Egyptians with all the plagues in the wildernesse.
\v 9 Bee strong, and quit your selues like men, O ye Philistines, that yee be not seruants vnto the Hebrewes, \x + \xo 4:9 \xt Iudg. 13.1.\x*as they haue bene to you: \f + \fr 4:9 \ft Hebr. Be men.\f*quit your selues like men, and fight.
\v 10 ¶ And the Philistines fought, and Israel was smitten, and they fled euery man into his tent: and there was a very great slaughter, for there fell of Israel thirtie thousand footmen.
\v 11 And the Arke of God was taken, and the two sonnes of Eli, Hophni, and Phinehas \f + \fr 4:11 \ft Hebr. died.\f*were slaine.
\v 12 ¶ And there ran a man of Beniamin out of the army, and came to Shiloh the same day with his clothes rent, and with earth vpon his head.
\v 13 And when hee came, loe, Eli sate vpon a seat by the way side, watching: for his heart trembled for the Arke of God. And when the man came into the citie, and told \add it\add*, all the city cried out.
\v 14 And when Eli heard the noise of the crying, hee said; What \add meaneth\add* the noise of this tumult? And the man came in hastily, and told Eli.
\v 15 Now Eli was ninetie and eight yeeres old, and \x + \xo 4:15 \xt Chap. 3.2.\x*his eyes \f + \fr 4:15 \ft Hebr. stood.\f*were dimme, that he could not see.
\v 16 And the man said vnto Eli, I \add am\add* he, that came out of the army, and I fled to day out of the army. And he said, What \f + \fr 4:16 \ft Hebr. is the thing.\f*is there done, my sonne?
\v 17 And the messenger answered, and said, Israel is fled before the Philistines, and there hath bene also a great slaughter among the people, and thy two sonnes also, Hophni & Phinehas, are dead, and the Arke of God is taken.
\v 18 And it came to passe when hee made mention of the Arke of God, that he fell from off the seat backward by the side of the gate, and his necke brake, and hee died: for hee was an old man, and heauie, and hee had iudged Israel fortie yeeres.
\v 19 ¶ And his daughter in law Phinehas wife was with childe neere \f + \fr 4:19 \ft Or, to crie out.\f*to be deliuered: and when shee heard the tidings that the Arke of God was taken, and that her father in law, and her husband were dead, shee bowed her selfe and traueyled; for her paines \f + \fr 4:19 \ft Hebr. were turned.\f*came vpon her.
\v 20 And about the time of her death, the women that stood by her, said vnto her: Feare not, for thou hast borne a sonne. But she answered not, \f + \fr 4:20 \ft Heb. set not her heart\f*neither did she regard \add it\add*.
\v 21 And she named the childe \f + \fr 4:21 \ft That is, where is the glory?\f*Ichabod, saying, \f + \fr 4:21 \ft Or, there is no glory.\f*The glory is departed from Israel, (because the Arke of God was taken, and because of her father in law and her husband.)
\v 22 And she said, The glory is departed from Israel: for the Arke of God is taken.
\c 5
\iex 1 The Philistines hauing brought the Arke into Ashdod, set it in the house of Dagon. 3 Dagon is smitten downe and cut in pieces, and they of Ashdod smitten with Emerods. 8 So God dealeth with them of Gath, when it was brought thither: 10 and so with them of Ekron when it was brought thither.
\v 1 ¶ And the Philistines tooke the Arke of God, and brought it from Ebenezer vnto Ashdod.
\v 2 When the Philistines tooke the Arke of God, they brought it into the house of Dagon, and set it by Dagon.
\v 3 ¶ And when they of Ashdod arose earely on the morrow, behold, Dagon \add was\add* fallen vpon his face to the earth, before the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*: and they tooke Dagon, and set him in his place againe.
\v 4 And when they arose earely on the morrow morning, behold, Dagon \add was\add* fallen vpon his face to the ground, before the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*: and the head of Dagon, and both the palmes of his hands \add were\add* cut off vpon the threshold, only \f + \fr 5:4 \ft Or, the filthy part.\f*the stumpe of Dagon was left to him.
\v 5 Therefore neither the priests of Dagon, nor any that come into Dagons house, tread on the threshold of Dagon in Ashdod vnto this day.
\v 6 But the hand of the \nd LORD\nd* was heauy vpon them of Ashdod, and he destroyed them, and smote them with \x + \xo 5:6 \xt Psal. 78.66.\x*Emerods, \add euen\add* Ashdod, and the coastes thereof.
\v 7 And when the men of Ashdod saw that \add it was\add* so, they said, The Arke of the God of Israel shall not abide with vs: for his hand is sore vpon vs, and vpon Dagon our god.
\v 8 They sent therefore, and gathered all the lords of the Philistines vnto them, and said, What shall we doe with the Arke of the God of Israel? And they answered, Let the Arke of the God of Israel bee caried about vnto Gath. And they caried the Arke of the God of Israel about \add thither\add*.
\v 9 And it was \add so\add*, that after they had caried it about, the hand of the \nd LORD\nd* was against the citie with a very great destruction: and hee smote the men of the citie both small and great, and they had Emerods in their secret parts.
\v 10 ¶ Therfore they sent the Arke of God to Ekron: and it came to passe as the Arke of God came to Ekron, that the Ekronites cried out, saying, They haue brought about the Arke of the God of Israel to vs, to slay vs, and our people.
\v 11 So they sent and gathered together all the lords of the Philistines, and said, Send away the Arke of the God of Israel, and let it goe againe to his owne place, that it slay vs not, and our people: for there was a deadly destruction throughout all the citie: The hand of God was very heauy there.
\v 12 And the men that died not, were smitten with the Emerods: and the cry of the citie went vp to heauen.
\c 6
\iex 1 After seuen moneths the Philistines take counsell, how to send backe the Arke. 10 They bring it on a new cart with an offering vnto Bethshemesh. 19 The people are smitten for looking into the Arke. 21 They send to them of Kiriath-iearim to fetch it.
\v 1 ¶ And the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd* was in the countrey of the Philistines seuen moneths.
\v 2 And the Philistines called for the priests and the diuiners, saying, What shall we doe to the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*? Tell vs wherewith we shall send it to his place?
\v 3 And they said, If yee send away the Arke of the God of Israel, send it not empty: but in any wise returne him a trespasse offring: then ye shall be healed, and it shall be knowen to you, why his hand is not remooued from you.
\v 4 Then said they, What \add shall be\add* the trespasse offering, which wee shall returne to him? They answered, Fiue golden Emerods, and fiue golden mice, \add according to\add* the number of the lordes of the Philistines: for one plague \add was\add* on \f + \fr 6:4 \ft Heb. them.\f*you all, and on your lords.
\v 5 Wherefore ye shall make images of your Emerodes, and images of your Mice, that marre the land, and ye shall giue glory vnto the God of Israel: peraduenture hee will lighten his hand from off you, and from off your gods, and from off your land.
\v 6 Wherefore then doe yee harden your hearts, as the Egyptians and Pharaoh hardened their hearts? when he had wrought \f + \fr 6:6 \ft Or, reprochfully.\f*wonderfully among them, \x + \xo 6:6 \xt Exod. 12.31.\x*did they not let \f + \fr 6:6 \ft Heb. them.\f*the people goe, and they departed?
\v 7 Now therefore make a new cart, and take two milch-kine, on which there hath come no yoke, and tie the kine to the cart, and bring the calues home from them.
\v 8 And take the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*, and lay it vpon the cart, and put the iewels of golde, which ye returne him \add for\add* a trespasse offering, in a coffer by the side thereof, and send it away, that it may goe.
\v 9 And see, if it goeth vp by the way of his owne coast to Bethshemesh, \add then\add* \f + \fr 6:9 \ft Or, it.\f*he hath done vs this great euill: but if not, then wee shall know that \add it is\add* not his hand \add that\add* smote vs; it \add was\add* a chance \add that\add* happened to vs.
\v 10 ¶ And the men did so: and tooke two milch-kine, and tied them to the cart, and shut vp their calues at home.
\v 11 And they layde the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd* vpon the cart, and the coffer, with the mice of golde, and the images of their Emerods.
\v 12 And the kine tooke the straight way to the way of Bethshemesh, \add and\add* went along the high way, lowing as they went, and turned not aside \add to\add* the right hand, or \add to\add* the left: and the lords of the Philistines went after them, vnto the border of Bethshemesh.
\v 13 And \add they of\add* Bethshemesh \add were\add* reaping their wheat haruest in the valley: and they lifted vp their eyes, and saw the Arke, and reioyced to see \add it\add*.
\v 14 And the cart came into the field of Ioshua a Bethshemite, & stood there, where \add there was\add* a great stone: and they claue the wood of the cart, and offered the kine, a burnt offering vnto the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 15 And the Leuites tooke downe the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*, and the coffer that \add was\add* with it, wherein the iewels of golde \add were\add*, and put \add them\add* on the great stone: And the men of Bethshemesh offered burnt offrings, and sacrificed sacrifices the same day vnto the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 16 And when the fiue lordes of the Philistines had seene \add it\add*, they returned to Ekron the same day.
\v 17 And these \add are\add* the golden Emerods which the Philistines returned \add for\add* a trespasse offering vnto the \nd LORD\nd*; for Ashdod one, for Gaza one, for Askelon one, for Gath one, for Ekron one.
\v 18 And the golden Mice \add according to\add* the number of all the cities of the Philistines, \add belonging\add* to the fiue lordes, \add both\add* of fenced cities, and of countrey villages, euen vnto the \f + \fr 6:18 \ft Or, great stone.\f*great \add stone of\add* Abel, whereon they set downe the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*; \add which stone remaineth\add* vnto this day, in the field of Ioshua the Bethshemite.
\v 19 ¶ And he smote the men of Bethshemesh, because they had looked into the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*, euen he smote of the people fiftie thousand, and threescore and tenne men: and the people lamented, because the \nd LORD\nd* had smitten \add many\add* of the people with a great slaughter.
\v 20 And the men of Bethshemesh said, Who is able to stand before this holy \nd LORD\nd* God? and to whom shal he goe vp from vs?
\v 21 ¶ And they sent messengers to the inhabitants of Kiriath-iearim, saying, The Philistines haue brought againe the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*; come ye downe, \add and\add* fetch it vp to you.
\c 7
\iex 1 They of Kiriath-iearim bring the Arke into the house of Abinadab, and sanctifie Eleazar his sonne to keepe it. 2 After twentie yeeres 3 The Israelites, by Samuels meanes, solemnly repent at Mizpeh. 7 While Samuel prayeth and sacrificeth, the \nd LORD\nd* discomfiteth the Philistines by thunder, at Eben-ezer. 13 The Philistines are subdued. 15 Samuel peaceably and religiously iudgeth Israel.
\v 1 ¶ And the men of Kiriath-iearim came, and fetcht vp the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*, and brought it into the house of Abinadab in the hill, and sanctified Eleazar his sonne, to keepe the Arke of the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 2 And it came to passe while the Arke abode in Kiriath-iearim, that the time was long: for it was twentie yeeres: and all the house of Israel lamented after the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 3 ¶ And Samuel spake vnto all the house of Israel, saying, If ye doe returne vnto the \nd LORD\nd* with all your hearts, \add then\add* \x + \xo 7:3 \xt Iosh. 14.15,23.\x*put away the strange gods, and \x + \xo 7:3 \xt Iudg. 2.13.\x*Ashtaroth from among you, and prepare your hearts vnto the \nd LORD\nd*, and \x + \xo 7:3 \xt Deut. 6.4. matt. 4.10. luke 4.8.\x*serue him onely: & he will deliuer you out of the hand of the Philistines.
\v 4 Then the children of Israel did put away \x + \xo 7:4 \xt Iudg. 2.11.\x*Baalim, and Ashtaroth, and serued the \nd LORD\nd* onely.
\v 5 And Samuel said, Gather all Israel to Mizpeh, and I will pray for you vnto the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 6 And they gathered together to Mizpeh, and drew water, and powred \add it\add* out before the \nd LORD\nd*, and fasted on that day, and said there, We haue sinned against the \nd LORD\nd*. And Samuel iudged the children of Israel in Mizpeh.
\v 7 And when the Philistines heard that the children of Israel were gathered together to Mizpeh, the lords of the Philistines went vp against Israel: and when the children of Israel heard \add it\add*, they were afraid of the Philistines.
\v 8 And the children of Israel said to Samuel, \f + \fr 7:8 \ft Heb. be not silent from vs from crying.\f*Cease not to crie vnto the \nd LORD\nd* our God for vs, that he will saue vs out of the hand of the Philistines.
\v 9 ¶ And Samuel tooke a sucking lambe, and offered \add it for\add* a burnt offering wholly vnto the \nd LORD\nd*; and Samuel cried vnto the \nd LORD\nd* for Israel, and the \nd LORD\nd* \f + \fr 7:9 \ft Or, answered.\f*heard him.
\v 10 And as Samuel was offering vp the burnt offering, the Philistines drewe neere to battell against Israel: but the \nd LORD\nd* thundred with a great thunder on that day vpon the Philistines, and discomfited them, and they were smitten before Israel.
\v 11 And the men of Israel went out of Mizpeh, and pursued the Philistines, and smote them, vntill \add they came\add* vnder Bethcar.
\v 12 Then Samuel tooke a stone, and set \add it\add* betweene Mizpeh and Shen, and called the name of it \f + \fr 7:12 \ft That is, the stone of helpe.\f*Eben-Ezer, saying, Hitherto hath the \nd LORD\nd* helped vs.
\v 13 ¶ So the Philistines were subdued, and they came no more into the coast of Israel: and the hand of the \nd LORD\nd* was against the Philistines, all the dayes of Samuel.
\v 14 And the cities which the Philistines had taken from Israel, were restored to Israel, from Ekron euen vnto Gath, and the coasts thereof did Israel deliuer out of the hands of the Philistines: and there was peace betweene Israel and the Amorites.
\v 15 And Samuel iudged Israel all the dayes of his life.
\v 16 And he went from yeere to yeere \f + \fr 7:16 \ft Heb. and he circuited.\f*in circuit to Bethel, and Gilgal, and Mizpeh, and iudged Israel in all those places.
\v 17 And his returne \add was\add* to Ramah: for there \add was\add* his house: and there hee iudged Israel, and there hee built an altar vnto the \nd LORD\nd*.
\c 8
\iex 1 By occasion of the ill gouernment of Samuels sonnes, the Israelites aske a King. 6 Samuel praying in griefe is comforted by God. 10 Hee telleth the manner of a King. 19 God willeth Samuel to yeeld vnto the importunitie of the people.
\v 1 ¶ And it came to passe, when Samuel was old, that he made his sonnes Iudges ouer Israel.
\v 2 Now the name of his first borne was Ioel, and the name of his second, Abiah: \add they were\add* Iudges in Beer-sheba.
\v 3 And his sonnes walked not in his wayes, but turned aside after lucre, and \x + \xo 8:3 \xt Deut. 16.19.\x*tooke bribes, & peruerted iudgement.
\v 4 Then all the Elders of Israel gathered themselues together, and came to Samuel vnto Ramah,
\v 5 And said vnto him, Behold, thou art olde, and thy sonnes walke not in thy wayes: now \x + \xo 8:5 \xt Ose. 13.10. acts 13.21.\x*make vs a King to iudge vs, like all the nations.
\v 6 ¶ But the thing \f + \fr 8:6 \ft Heb. was euill in the eyes of Samuel.\f*displeased Samuel, when they said, Giue vs a King to iudge vs: and Samuel prayed vnto the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 7 And the \nd LORD\nd* said vnto Samuel, Hearken vnto the voyce of the people in all that they say vnto thee: for they haue not reiected thee, but they haue reiected mee, that I should not reigne ouer them.
\v 8 According to all the works which they haue done since the day that I brought them vp out of Egypt euen vnto this day, wherewith they haue forsaken me, and serued other gods: so doe they also vnto thee.
\v 9 Nowe therefore \f + \fr 8:9 \ft Or, obey.\f*hearken vnto their voyce: \f + \fr 8:9 \ft Or, notwithstanding, when thou hast solemnly protested against them, then thou shalt shew, &c.\f*howbeit, yet protest solemnly vnto them, and shew them the maner of the King that shall reigne ouer them.
\v 10 ¶ And Samuel told all the words of the \nd LORD\nd* vnto the people, that asked of him a King.
\v 11 And hee sayd, This will be the maner of the king that shall reigne ouer you: Hee will take your sonnes, and appoint \add them\add* for himselfe for his charets, and \add to bee\add* his horsemen, and \add some\add* shall runne before his charets.
\v 12 And hee will appoint him Captaines ouer thousands, and captaines ouer fifties, and \add will set them\add* to eare his ground, and to reape his haruest, and to make his instruments of warre, and instruments of his charets.
\v 13 And he will take your daughters \add to be\add* confectionaries, and \add to be\add* cookes, and \add to be\add* bakers.
\v 14 And he will take your fields, and your vineyards, and your oliue-yards, \add euen\add* the best \add of them\add*, and giue \add them\add* to his seruants.
\v 15 And he will take the tenth of your seed, and of your vineyards, and giue to his \f + \fr 8:15 \ft Heb. Eunuches.\f*officers, and to his seruants.
\v 16 And hee will take your men seruants, and your mayd seruants, and your goodliest young men, and your asses, and put \add them\add* to his worke.
\v 17 Hee will take the tenth of your sheepe, and ye shall be his seruants.
\v 18 And ye shall cry out in that day, because of your king which ye shall haue chosen you; and the \nd LORD\nd* will not heare you in that day.
\v 19 ¶ Neuerthelesse, the people refused to obey the voyce of Samuel; and they said, Nay, but we will haue a King ouer vs:
\v 20 That we also may be like all the nations, and that our King may iudge vs, and goe out before vs, and fight our battels.
\v 21 And Samuel heard all the words of the people, and he rehearsed them in the eares of the \nd LORD\nd*.
\v 22 And the \nd LORD\nd* said to Samuel, Hearken vnto their voyce, and make them a King. And Samuel said vnto the men of Israel, Goe yee euery man vnto his citie.
\c 9
\iex 1 Saul despairing to finde his fathers asses, 6 by the counsell of his seruaunt, 11 and direction of young maidens, 15 according to Gods reuelation, 18 commeth to Samuel. 19 Samuel entertaineth Saul at the feast. 25 Samuel after secret communication, bringeth Saul on his way.
\v 1 ¶ Now there was a man of Beniamin, whose name \add was\add* \x + \xo 9:1 \xt Chap. 14.51. 1.chro. 8.33.\x*Kish, the sonne of Abiel, the sonne of Zeror, the sonne of Bechorath, the sonne of Aphiah, a \f + \fr 9:1 \ft Or, the sonne of a man of Iemini.\f*Beniamite, a mighty man of \f + \fr 9:1 \ft Or, substance.\f*power.
\v 2 And he had a sonne, whose name \add was\add* Saul, a choice young man, and a goodly: and \add there was\add* not among the children of Israel a goodlier person then hee: from his shoulders and vpward, hee was higher then any of the people.
\v 3 And the asses of Kish, Sauls father, were lost; and Kish said to Saul his sonne, Take nowe one of the seruants with thee, and arise, goe seeke the asses.
\v 4 And he passed thorow mount Ephraim, and passed thorow the land of Shalisha, but they found \add them\add* not: then they passed thorow the land of Shalim, and \add there they were\add* not: and hee passed thorow the land of the Beniamites, but they found \add them\add* not.
\v 5 \add And\add* when they were come to the land of Zuph, Saul said to his seruant that \add was\add* with him, Come, and let vs returne, lest my father leaue \add caring\add* for the asses, and take thought for vs.
\v 6 And hee said vnto him, Behold now, \add there is\add* in this citie a man of God, and \add he is\add* an honourable man; all that he saith, commeth surely to passe: Now let vs goe thither; peraduenture he can shew vs our way that we should goe.
\v 7 Then said Saul to his seruaunt, But behold, \add if\add* we goe, what shall wee bring the man? for the bread is \f + \fr 9:7 \ft Hebr is gone out of &c.\f*spent in our vessels, and \add there is\add* not a present to bring to the man of God: What \f + \fr 9:7 \ft Hebr. is with vs?\f*haue wee?
\v 8 And the seruant answered Saul againe, and said, \f + \fr 9:8 \ft Hebr. there is found in my hand.\f*Behold, I haue here at hand the fourth part of a shekel of siluer; \add that\add* wil I giue to the man of God, to tell vs our way.
\v 9 (Beforetime in Israel, when a man went to enquire of God, thus he spake; Come, and let vs go to the Seer: for \add he that is\add* now \add called\add* a Prophet, was beforetime called a Seer.)
\v 10 Then said Saul to his seruant, \f + \fr 9:10 \ft Hebr. thy word is good.\f*Wel said, come, let vs go: so they went vnto the city where the man of God \add was\add*.
\v 11 ¶ \add And\add* as they went vp \f + \fr 9:11 \ft Hebr. in the ascent of the citie.\f*the hill to the city, they found yong maydens going out to draw water, and said vnto them, Is the Seer here?
\v 12 And they answered them, and said, He is: behold, \add he is\add* before you, make haste now: for he came to day to the citie; for \add there is\add* \f + \fr 9:12 \ft Or, feast.\f*a sacrifice of the people to day in the hie place.
